@node "INTRO" "Introduction for Multi-Top V1.2"

                               @{u}@{b}INTRODUCTION@{ub}@{uu}

Well the main reason why this program was written was the fact that in the
first days of using the great FAME Software no such a Program exists, and
so I decided to write my own one.

Multi-Top was always programmed with speed in mind, so it has NO nice GUI
or other so called "user-friendly" interface, just a simply textfile with
a fixed order of the entry is all it needs. This lacks a bit the usage but
gives your BBS a minimum of OFFLINE time required to create the BBS stats.


@{b}mULTI-tOP requires the following things to work properly:@{ub}

 @{b}-@{ub} Kickstart V3.x (don't ask for lower support, better upgrade!)

 @{b}-@{ub} FAME.library V5+ (without it mULTI-tOP won't work!) 

 @{b}-@{ub} An installed FAME Version (you may also test this Program with only your
   user.data/user.keys on another Amiga to check things out...)


@{b}...and you get the following features:@{ub}

 @{b}-@{ub} The faastest (I think!) Bullcreator ever written, creates 14 bulls with
   568 Users found in the user.data in less than 9 sec. on my A4000/040 !

 @{b}-@{ub} Configurable via Textfile for maximum speed

 @{b}-@{ub} Supports for every bull an own external Bullheader (V0.5).

 @{b}-@{ub} Supports 64-Bit Calculations for User's Upload/Download bytes and also
   for the total system byte statistics up to 18TB (V0.60).
@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "How to install it to your system"

                               @{b}@{u}INSTALLATION@{ub}@{uu}

Well best is (as always) to use the Installer Script supplied with this
archive. It will copy all files to the right place for you. If you wish
to install it by hand, follow these short instructions:

@{b}1.@{ub} Copy mULTI-tOP and the mULTI-tOP.cfg file from the Bin/ directory to
   a place where you have stored all your other doors. (Of course copy
   only the version of mULTI-tOP which fits to your processor equipment!).
   You should also copy the history file (and read it!) and the guide
   file to a place of your choice.

@{b}2.@{ub} If you wish to use the supplied HeaderFiles for your bulls copy the
   whole Header/ directory to the directory where you have copied 
   mULTI-tOP. You may of course delete unwanted headers or change them,
   the supplied ones are only examples!

@{b}3.@{ub} Now start your favourite Texteditor and edit the mULTI-tOP.cfg file
   to fit your requirements. After this, just go into a shell, CD into
   the mULTI-tOP directory and type mULTI-tOP to create all bulls.

4. To use mULTi-tOP on every logoff, you have to create another Textfile
   which starts mULTI-tOP to create the bulls. A valid Textfile maybe this:

   @{b}--------- CUT HERE! ---------@{ub}

   FAME:Doors/mULTI-TOP

   @{b}--------- CUT HERE! ---------@{ub}

   That's it! Now set the S-Bit of that Script and copy this textfile to
   @{fg shine}FAME:Node<X>/NodeBatches/LogOffBatches/@{fg text} under a name of your choice.
   You have to replace <X> with the according Node Number. FAME will now
   execute this script on every logoff for the according node.
@endnode

@node "CONFIG" "Description of the Config File"

                               @{b}@{u}CONFIGURATION@{ub}@{uu}

The config file of mULTI-tOP is a plain textfile with a fixed order of the
entries to gain more speed when parsing this file. Every line has a special
meaning which will be described below. 

Here is an example mULTi-tOP.cfg file:

@{b}--------- CUT HERE! ---------@{ub}

FAME:USER.dATA
BULLETINS:BULL4.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL5.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL6.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL7.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL8.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL9.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL10.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL11.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL12.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL13.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL14.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL15.TXT
BULLETINS:BULL16.TXT
pUNISHMENT iNC.
10
SHOWSYSOP

@{b}--------- CUT HERE! ---------@{ub}

@{u}Description of Configfile@{uu}

Multitop only take care about the first 16 lines of this configfile, all other
lines are ignored. If you don't want to create all bulletins, simply write
a '-' instead of the path and filename for the bull, so Multi-Top skips this
entry.

 1. Line: Path & name to user.data
 2. Line: Path & name for the User-List
 3. Line: Path & name for Top Uploaders (bytes)
 4. Line: Path & name for Top Downloaders (bytes)
 5. Line: Path & name for Top Uploaders (files)
 6. Line: Path & name for Top Downloaders (files)
 7. Line: Path & name for Top Upload CPS
 8. Line: Path & name for Top Download CPS
 9. Line: Path & name for Top Callers
10. Line: Path & name for Top Message Writers
11. Line: Path & name for Top Nuked Bytes
12. Line: Path & name for Top Nuked Files
13. Line: Path & name for Top SysOp-Chatters
14. Line: Path & name for Top overall Hacks
15. Line: Name of your BBS
16. Line: Amount of Users to display (User-List ignores!)
17. Line: If SHOWSYSOP is set, the SysOp will be added to the bulls.

I think this should be clear. If any error occures start mULTi-tOP in a
shell and watch it's output, so it should be easy to fix any error.
@endnode

@node "USAGE" "How to use mULTi-tOP"

                                   @{u}@{b}USAGE@{ub}@{uu}

As described in Chapter @{"INSTALLATION" LINK "INSTALLATION"} you only have to create a textfile
which starts mULTI-TOP and the show will begin. Multi-Top reads in all
your user.datas and starts then in memory with all bulletin creations
without loading in the user.data more than one time. This is the main
reason for the speed of mULTI-tOP but results also in more memory usage,
so you could be sure that mULTI-tOP requires about 2 times the size of
your user.datas as temporary memory pool (This is the main reason why
mULTI-tOP uses Kick 3.x Memory Pools...).

                                @{u}The Headers@{uu}

mULTI-tOP supports for all bulletins a specific header which will be
on top of the according stats. To use this feature, create a directory
called Header/ (see Installation) and copy for every bulletin you wish
to have a header the files under the following filenames:

    UL_BYTES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Bytes Uploader Bull
    DL_BYTES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Bytes Downloader Bull
    UL_FILES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Files Uploader Bull
    DL_FILES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Files Downloader Bull
      UL_CPS.TXT  ---> Header for the Top CPS Uploading Bull
      DL_CPS.TXT  ---> Header for the Top CPS Downloading Bull
     CALLERS.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Callers Bull
    MESSAGES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Message Writer Bull
 NUKED_BYTES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Nuked Bytes Bull
 NUKED_FILES.TXT  ---> Header for the Top Nuked Files Bull
       CHATS.TXT  ---> Header for the Top SysOp-Chatters Bull
    USERLIST.TXT  ---> Header for the User-List Bull
       HACKS.TXT  ---> Header for the Top overall hacks Bull (V0.60)

You do not have to use these files, if you want no header for a specific bull,
simply delete the according file and mULTI-tOP will create the bull without
the header.
@endnode

